and_Media_in_Contemporary_Bali?f_ri=221567", "dom_id": "work_60169177", "summary": null, "downloadable_attachments": [{"id": 73729231, "asset_id": 60169177, "asset_type": "Work", "always_allow_download": false}], "ordered_authors": [{"id": 95368833, "first_name": "Brita", "last_name": "Heimarck", "domain_name": "independent", "page_name": "BritaHeimarck", "display_name": "Brita Heimarck", "profile_url": "https://independent.academia.edu/BritaHeimarck?f_ri=221567", "photo": "/images/s65_no_pic.png"}], "research_interests": [{"id": 177125, "name": "Language Culture and Communication", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Language_Culture_and_Communication?f_ri=221567", "nofollow": false}]}, {"id": 48593971, "title": "Embodiment, Balinese Theatre and the Ethnographer's Predicament", "created_at": "2021-05-05T00:05:08.456-07:00", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/48593971/Embodiment_Balinese_Theatre_and_the_Ethnographers_Predicament?f_ri=221567", "dom_id": "work_48593971", "summary": null, "downloadable_attachments": [{"id": 67125227, "asset_id": 48593971, "asset_type": "Work", "always_allow_download": false}], "ordered_authors": [{"id": 6925295, "first_name": "Jane", "last_name": "Turner", "domain_name": "mmu", "page_name": "JaneTurner", "display_name": "Jane  Turner", "profile_url": "https://mmu.academia.edu/JaneTurner?f_ri=221567", "photo": "/images/s65_no_pic.png"}], "research_interests": [{"id": 767, "name": "Anthropology", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Anthropology?f_ri=221567", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 29102, "name": "Theatre", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Theatre?f_ri=221567", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 29167, "name": "Dance", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Dance?f_ri=221567", "nofollow": false}]}, {"id": 44282313, "title": "A Very Peculiar Practice", "created_at": "2020-10-12T14:08:53.281-07:00", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/44282313/A_Very_Peculiar_Practice?f_ri=221567", "dom_id": "work_44282313", "summary": "Media Studies is often dismissed by older, established (aka often moribund) disciplines as not being a 'serious' intellectual endeavour. So, for my inaugural lecture a Professor of Critical Media and Cultural Studies at SOAS, University of London in May 2010, I had fun by showing just how inadequate the self-styles serious disciplines are at interpreting what is going on and what engages one of the largest audiences in the non-Western world. Using ethnography from Bali, Indonesia, I start by questioning the supposed wisdom of conventional scholarship to show just how peculiar, hermetically sealed and even intellectually vacuous much of the scholarly work on the island is. I then turn to that favourite object of derision among self-important scholars: television. A critical analysis of a range of genres suggests that, perhaps unsurprisingly, the triviality of such popular culture is only sustainable by sheer ignorance and out-of-hand dismissals achieved by not actually knowing anything about what they opine. Engaging with Balinese and Indonesian popular culture offers remarkable surprises. I illustrate the talk with a range of slides and video clips\u2014many of them amusing\u2014that invite the audience to rethink their prejudices. After all, there are practices, including academic ones, far more peculiar than Media Studies.\r\nVideo of the original lecture: https://youtu.be/dvOtqRN3eqc ", "downloadable_attachments": [{"id": 64662341, "asset_id": 44282313, "asset_type": "Work", "always_allow_download": false}], "ordered_authors": [{"id": 3770, "first_name": "Mark", "last_name": "Hobart", "domain_name": "soas", "page_name": "MarkHobart", "display_name": "Mark  Hobart", "profile_url": "https://soas.academia.edu/MarkHobart?f_ri=221567", "photo": "https://0.academia-photos.com/3770/18767681/18728398/s65_mark.hobart.jpg"}], "research_interests": [{"id": 3499, "name": "Social and Cultural Anthropology", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Social_and_Cultural_Anthropology?f_ri=221567", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 4707, "name": "Indonesian Studies", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Indonesian_Studies?f_ri=221567", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 221567, "name": "Balinese Studies", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Balinese_Studies?f_ri=221567", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 3783568, "name": "Critical Cultural and Media Studies", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Critical_Cultural_and_Media_Studies?f_ri=221567", "nofollow": false}]}, {"id": 42186955, "title": "Bibliography -Mark Hobart", "created_at": "2020-03-10T11:42:28.230-07:00", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/42186955/Bibliography_Mark_Hobart?f_ri=221567", "dom_id": "work_42186955", "summary": "A summary of published and unpublished work available on my personal website.", "downloadable_attachments": [{"id": 62329864, "asset_id": 42186955, "asset_type": "Work", "always_allow_download": false}], "ordered_authors": [{"id": 3770, "first_name": "Mark", "last_name": "Hobart", "domain_name": "soas", "page_name": "MarkHobart", "display_name": "Mark  Hobart", "profile_url": "https://soas.academia.edu/MarkHobart?f_ri=221567", "photo": "https://0.academia-photos.com/3770/18767681/18728398/s65_mark.hobart.jpg"}], "research_interests": [{"id": 934, "name": "Media and Cultural Studies", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Media_and_Cultural_Studies?f_ri=221567", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 1031, "name": "Southeast Asian Studies", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Southeast_Asian_Studies?f_ri=221567", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 3499, "name": "Social and Cultural Anthropology", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Social_and_Cultural_Anthropology?f_ri=221567", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 16106, "name": "Anthropology of Development", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Anthropology_of_Development?f_ri=221567", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 23947, "name": "History and Philosophy of the Human Sciences", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/History_and_Philosophy_of_the_Human_Sciences?f_ri=221567"}, {"id": 221567, "name": "Balinese Studies", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Balinese_Studies?f_ri=221567"}, {"id": 458605, "name": "Theatre and Performance Studies", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Theatre_and_Performance_Studies?f_ri=221567"}]}, {"id": 42110712, "title": "Review of Geertz & Geertz - Kinship in Bali with postscript", "created_at": "2020-03-01T14:04:55.599-08:00", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/42110712/Review_of_Geertz_and_Geertz_Kinship_in_Bali_with_postscript?f_ri=221567", "dom_id": "work_42110712", "summary": "A difficulty in the study of Balinese society is the complex variation between regions and even villages\u2014perhaps, in part, as a consequence of the island\u2019s extreme Balkanization in the past. The eminent authors of this monograph pay close attention to this as they develop, and at points modify, their analysis from previous works. In an adventurous argument, they confront the formidable problems of Balinese kinship and its social context; and set out to explain the diversity in terms of a general model of variability. Although the point of departure is their own ethnography, their ultimate concern is with \u2018the operation of kinship symbolization\u2019 as part of a wider \u2018culture pattern\u2019 of forms on the ground is to be understood in terms of \u2018variations on a set ideational themes\u2019 in \u2018the cultural dimensions of kinship\u2019, and this emphasis is central to an appreciation of their approach. ", "downloadable_attachments": [{"id": 62243229, "asset_id": 42110712, "asset_type": "Work", "always_allow_download": false}], "ordered_authors": [{"id": 3770, "first_name": "Mark", "last_name": "Hobart", "domain_name": "soas", "page_name": "MarkHobart", "display_name": "Mark  Hobart", "profile_url": "https://soas.academia.edu/MarkHobart?f_ri=221567", "photo": "https://0.academia-photos.com/3770/18767681/18728398/s65_mark.hobart.jpg"}], "research_interests": [{"id": 3499, "name": "Social and Cultural Anthropology", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Social_and_Cultural_Anthropology?f_ri=221567", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 221567, "name": "Balinese Studies", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Balinese_Studies?f_ri=221567", "nofollow": false}]}, {"id": 39001919, "title": "9 FOREIGN FEMALE INTERVENTIONS IN TRADITIONAL ASIAN ARTS", "created_at": "2019-05-02T06:29:42.336-07:00", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/39001919/9_FOREIGN_FEMALE_INTERVENTIONS_IN_TRADITIONAL_ASIAN_ARTS?f_ri=221567", "dom_id": "work_39001919", "summary": "The powerful patriarchal forces that discourage or erase female participation in traditional Asian performing arts were disrupted in the late twentieth century by some bold and passionate female artists who came from Europe and America to devote themselves to the study and performance of forms that were, allegedly, exclusively male. To focus on the work of Western artists in a book on women in Asian performance may seem inappropriate, even colonialist, but it is important to acknowledge that, especially in traditional arts, cultural expectations and taboos have been problematic for Asian female performers. On the other hand, women from outside Asian culture often occupy a privileged position and are granted greater freedom to pursue their interests. This chapter will use the work of two such \"pioneers\" as case studies to examine the ways that foreign female theatre artists, unbound by conventional expectations that might hinder Asian women, have asserted themselves in ways that local women might not. It will also consider whether these interventions have helped to change attitudes and create more opportunities for Asian female performers. One question that might arise at the outset is why Western women would seek to enter the doubly foreign world of an Asian theatre tradition performed by members of the opposite sex. Certainly neither of these artists set out to break gender or cultural barriers, nor were they driven to find some unique approach to an exotic form. On the contrary, both have asserted that these arts \"found\" them. Of course, this didn't happen by chance; rather, a particular set of historical and cultural circumstances came together to make these encounters possible. One element was the shift in geopolitical focus among Western nations after the Second World War from Europe to Asia, prompted by revolution in China, postcolonial tumult in South and Southeast Asia and the cautious cultural and political transition underway in postwar Japan. Moreover, the 1960s and 1970s were years that saw political, social and cultural upheaval in Europe and America, with protests against", "downloadable_attachments": [{"id": 59109447, "asset_id": 39001919, "asset_type": "Work", "always_allow_download": false}], "ordered_authors": [{"id": 9063314, "first_name": "MJ", "last_name": "Coldiron", "domain_name": "east15", "page_name": "MJColdiron", "display_name": "MJ  Coldiron", "profile_url": "https://east15.academia.edu/MJColdiron?f_ri=221567", "photo": "https://0.academia-photos.com/9063314/3418378/19264041/s65_mj.coldiron.jpg"}], "research_interests": [{"id": 1138, "name": "Women's Studies", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Womens_Studies?f_ri=221567", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 98424, "name": "Asian Theatre and Performance", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Asian_Theatre_and_Performance?f_ri=221567", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 274212, "name": "Japanese noh theatre, Japanese/Asian performing arts", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Japanese_noh_theatre_Japanese_Asian_performing_arts?f_ri=221567", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 537777, "name": "Balinese Mask Dance Drama, Peformance Studies", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Balinese_Mask_Dance_Drama_Peformance_Studies?f_ri=221567", "nofollow": false}]}, {"id": 35623318, "title": "Is interpretation incompatible with knowledge? The problem of whether the Javanese shadow play has meaning.", "created_at": "2018-01-09T10:35:15.249-08:00", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/35623318/Is_interpretation_incompatible_with_knowledge_The_problem_of_whether_the_Javanese_shadow_play_has_meaning?f_ri=221567", "dom_id": "work_35623318", "summary": null, "downloadable_attachments": [{"id": 55491590, "asset_id": 35623318, "asset_type": "Work", "always_allow_download": false}], "ordered_authors": [{"id": 3770, "first_name": "Mark", "last_name": "Hobart", "domain_name": "soas", "page_name": "MarkHobart", "display_name": "Mark  Hobart", "profile_url": "https://soas.academia.edu/MarkHobart?f_ri=221567", "photo": "https://0.academia-photos.com/3770/18767681/18728398/s65_mark.hobart.jpg"}], "research_interests": [{"id": 2863738, "name": "Social and Cultural Anthropology, Indonesian Studies, Philosophy", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Social_and_Cultural_Anthropology_Indonesian_Studies_Philosophy?f_ri=221567", "nofollow": false}]}, {"id": 26123169, "title": "Flat Puppets on an Empty Screen, Stories in the Round (2016)", "created_at": "2016-06-14T01:22:06.100-07:00", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/26123169/Flat_Puppets_on_an_Empty_Screen_Stories_in_the_Round_2016_?f_ri=221567", "dom_id": "work_26123169", "summary": "The puppets are flat, the screen against which they are placed and moved is white and devoid of scenery. In what kinds of space do the stories of the classical shadow-play of Java, Bali, Lombok, and the Malay world unfold despite this double flatness? How do performers use not only puppets and screen but also music and language to bring space into being? What must spectators know and do to make sense of these storytelling techniques? As a contribution to the narratological study of the multimodal making of storyworlds, I demonstrate that wayang kulit caters for different degrees of interpretive competence, which yield different understandings of the space that wayang portrays. An expert way of apprehending space requires seeing beyond the screen, puppets, and silhouettes, or even looking away from them. At the same time the peculiar ways of narrating space in wayang point to a deeply felt spatiality in real-life contexts as well.", "downloadable_attachments": [{"id": 48507612, "asset_id": 26123169, "asset_type": "Work", "always_allow_download": false}], "ordered_authors": [{"id": 819221, "first_name": "Bernard", "last_name": "Arps", "domain_name": "leidenuniv", "page_name": "BernardArps", "display_name": "Bernard Arps", "profile_url": "https://leidenuniv.academia.edu/BernardArps?f_ri=221567", "photo": "https://0.academia-photos.com/819221/284134/336041/s65_bernard.arps.jpg"}], "research_interests": [{"id": 787, "name": "Folklore", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Folklore?f_ri=221567", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 1031, "name": "Southeast Asian Studies", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Southeast_Asian_Studies?f_ri=221567", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 1987, "name": "Ethnomusicology", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Ethnomusicology?f_ri=221567", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 2193, "name": "Spatial Practices", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Spatial_Practices?f_ri=221567", "nofollow": false}, {"id": 2601, "name": "Film Music And Sound", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Film_Music_And_Sound?f_ri=221567"}, {"id": 3116, "name": "Space and Place", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Space_and_Place?f_ri=221567"}, {"id": 3190, "name": "Puppetry", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Puppetry?f_ri=221567"}, {"id": 3658, "name": "Anthropology of Performance", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Anthropology_of_Performance?f_ri=221567"}, {"id": 4490, "name": "Cognitive Narratology", "url": "https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Cognitive_Narratology?f_ri=221567"}, {"id": 4707, "name": "Indonesian Studies", "url": "https: